				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f_b(K;\beta _1,\beta _2) = \frac{{{\Gamma}(\beta _1 + \beta _2)}}{{{\Gamma}(\beta _1){\Gamma}(\beta _2)}}K^{\beta _1 - 1}(1 - K)^{\beta _2 - 1},$$\end{document}where β1 and β2 are the shape parameters. Note that this beta distribution is a parsimonious choice which we prefer to other unbounded distributions (e.g., Weibull and extreme value distributions) used in the literature45,46. We stress however that our framework is not limited to the use of beta distributions but can easily adopt other distributions if they appear more suitable in some regions (e.g., Australia and Western Sahara). These shape parameters can be expressed by the mean (μ) and standard deviation (σ) of the distribution47,6β1=μ(μ−μ2−σ2)σ2,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
